1
00:02:17,040 --> 00:02:18,724
Monsieur Rom...

2
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:26,531
Opar.

3
00:02:27,520 --> 00:02:29,409
(INHALES DEEPLY)

4
00:02:29,480 --> 00:02:31,721
We found it.

5
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:41,446
Captain Moulle?

6
00:02:46,200 --> 00:02:48,089
Form your lines.

7
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:49,527
(GUNS COCKING)

8
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:57,609
Maxims ready, sir!

9
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:05,010
CAPTAIN MOULLE: Steady.

10
00:03:10,840 --> 00:03:12,444
Wait.

11
00:03:21,240 --> 00:03:22,366
Fire!

12
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:36,321
(GUNFIRE STOPS)

13
00:03:43,040 --> 00:03:44,326
CAPTAIN MOULLE: Fall in!

14
00:04:38,200 --> 00:04:39,201
(YELLS)

15
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:41,605
(MEN GRUNTING)

16
00:04:57,560 --> 00:04:59,164
Stand your ground!

17
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:16,721
(GROANING)

18
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:13,165
(GRUNTING)

19
00:06:18,600 --> 00:06:19,965
(CHOKING)

20
00:06:36,680 --> 00:06:39,160
Chief Mbonga, I presume?

21
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:42,049
How do you know my name?

22
00:06:43,960 --> 00:06:45,644
You're the man I came to see.

23
00:07:02,680 --> 00:07:04,921
These are what you came for.

24
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:12,889
What would you do for them?

25
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:16,529
Whatever is necessary.

26
00:07:17,960 --> 00:07:22,602
There is one thing I desire
above all else.

27
00:07:23,480 --> 00:07:25,209
Bring it to me.

28
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:28,081
Bring him to me.

29
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:30,967
And you shall have your diamonds.

30
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:37,169
All I need is a name.

31
00:08:14,520 --> 00:08:18,047
His Serene Highness,
King Leopold of Belgium,

32
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:21,409
has extended an invitation
to Lord Greystoke

33
00:08:21,560 --> 00:08:25,485
to take a royal tour
of the Congo Free State

34
00:08:25,640 --> 00:08:28,086
to visit the schools
and churches he's built

35
00:08:28,640 --> 00:08:32,167
to acknowledge the success
of his anti-slavery initiatives

36
00:08:32,360 --> 00:08:34,601
and to open trade discussions.

37
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:36,690
(WALNUT SHELLS CRACKING)

38
00:08:41,640 --> 00:08:46,168
Lord Greystoke,
let me explain the Africa situation.

39
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:47,801
Mmm.

40
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:52,444
King Leopold controls the Congo.

41
00:08:53,080 --> 00:08:54,969
He's defaulting on his loans,

42
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:58,249
and needs a business partner
to fill the gap.

43
00:08:58,400 --> 00:09:01,131
Your invitation is a perfect opportunity

44
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:04,124
for Her Majesty's government
to get involved.

45
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:08,527
Consider the jobs we would create
for the poor natives of the Congo.

46
00:09:08,960 --> 00:09:10,610
- (SHELLS CLANKING)
- (GEORGE GROANS)

47
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:13,840
And I thought the Civil War was long.

48
00:09:13,960 --> 00:09:16,281
Dr. Williams, you are a guest here.

49
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:18,886
GEORGE: Prime Minister,
if you're not going to say it,

50
00:09:20,640 --> 00:09:21,846
allow me.

51
00:09:22,040 --> 00:09:24,805
You are Tarzan.

52
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:28,163
Lord of the Apes, King of the Jungle.

53
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:30,129
"Me Tarzan, you Jane!"

54
00:09:30,280 --> 00:09:32,328
Tarzan! Tarzan.

55
00:09:34,080 --> 00:09:36,890
King Leopold's inviting you
because you're a celebrity.

56
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:39,771
He wants to show you
the schools and churches he built.

57
00:09:39,920 --> 00:09:42,287
You "ooh" and "ah"
in front of the newspapers,

58
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:45,722
and he's validated
by Africa's favorite son.

59
00:09:46,760 --> 00:09:50,606
England pays his debts. We make money.

60
00:09:50,760 --> 00:09:53,286
- Ham sandwich. Easy.
- Hmm.

61
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:56,291
So, Your Majesties,

62
00:09:56,440 --> 00:09:59,364
can we get this show on the road?

63
00:10:05,840 --> 00:10:06,841
(SLURPS)

64
00:10:15,040 --> 00:10:16,041
No.

65
00:10:16,200 --> 00:10:17,850
- No?
- For Heaven's sake, why not?

66
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,446
Well, I've already seen Africa.

67
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:23,401
And it's hot.

68
00:10:24,040 --> 00:10:26,566
Excuse me? Did you say "hot"?

69
00:10:30,040 --> 00:10:33,044
Please send my apologies
to His Serene Highness.

70
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,571
And my name isn't Tarzan.

71
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:42,688
It's John Clayton III.

72
00:10:42,840 --> 00:10:45,844
Son of John and Lady Alice Clayton.

73
00:10:46,040 --> 00:10:50,090
Fifth Earl of Greystoke,
member of the House of Lords.

74
00:10:57,080 --> 00:10:58,764
GEORGE: Mr. Clayton.

75
00:10:58,920 --> 00:11:01,400
Lord Clayton. My apologies.

76
00:11:01,560 --> 00:11:04,450
George Washington Williams.
Diplomatic envoy for the United States.

77
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:06,927
- I was sent by President Harrison.
- JOHN: To do what?

78
00:11:07,080 --> 00:11:08,605
Join up with the Queen's emissary.

79
00:11:08,760 --> 00:11:12,082
America was the first country to recognize
King Leopold's claim on the Congo.

80
00:11:12,720 --> 00:11:15,041
You don't want to lose
your place at the trough.

81
00:11:15,200 --> 00:11:16,440
Look...

82
00:11:17,560 --> 00:11:20,450
I need your invitation to get in.

83
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:25,322
I'm afraid my intentions aren't exactly what
I expressed to your government or mine.

84
00:11:27,600 --> 00:11:30,444
And what exactly
do you want, Dr. Williams?

85
00:11:32,320 --> 00:11:36,564
Leopold spent the last seven years
getting control of the Congo.

86
00:11:36,720 --> 00:11:39,200
He used up his entire fortune
building that railroad of his,

87
00:11:39,360 --> 00:11:42,204
then shut off access
to 99% of the country.

88
00:11:42,360 --> 00:11:43,327
Why?

89
00:11:43,480 --> 00:11:45,482
Because he wants to be
the first monarch in history

90
00:11:45,680 --> 00:11:48,126
who doesn't want people
to see his good deeds?

91
00:11:48,280 --> 00:11:49,964
I don't buy it.

92
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:52,250
Tell me this, Lord Clayton.

93
00:11:52,440 --> 00:11:57,401
How does a bankrupt king
keep the whole of the Congo working?

94
00:11:59,960 --> 00:12:01,121
Slavery?

95
00:12:02,600 --> 00:12:05,809
I hope I'm wrong, but I need to know.

96
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:10,167
And for the sake of your friends
back home, you do, too.

97
00:12:12,320 --> 00:12:16,370
Accept Leopold's invitation
and take me with you.

98
00:12:16,520 --> 00:12:19,000
You know Africa off the beaten path.

99
00:12:19,160 --> 00:12:21,606
The languages, the people, the customs.

100
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:23,685
If we find anything amiss,

101
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:28,721
then I need someone to tell the world
that they'll believe.

102
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:39,009
I'll make all the arrangements.

103
00:12:39,160 --> 00:12:41,162
I'll see you in Liverpool.

104
00:12:48,360 --> 00:12:49,407
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

105
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:01,730
(COWS MOOING)

106
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:13,771
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

107
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:16,165
JOHN CLAYTON II: My family.

108
00:13:18,720 --> 00:13:21,451
I have done all I can to protect them.

109
00:13:25,320 --> 00:13:28,449
We have been surrounded by predators
since the shipwreck.

110
00:13:28,520 --> 00:13:30,045
(INFANT CRYING)

111
00:13:30,880 --> 00:13:32,769
The jungle consumes everything.

112
00:13:34,160 --> 00:13:38,245
It preys on the old, the sick,
the wounded, the weak.

113
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:40,402
But never the strong.

114
00:13:44,080 --> 00:13:46,560
Today, I buried my Alice.

115
00:13:47,840 --> 00:13:49,763
My dear Alice.

116
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:53,571
Now I fear for my child.

117
00:13:56,360 --> 00:13:57,771
God help us.

118
00:13:57,840 --> 00:13:58,841
(SNORTS)

119
00:13:59,040 --> 00:14:00,530
God help him.

120
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:01,681
(DISTANT ROARING)

121
00:14:16,800 --> 00:14:17,801
(GRUNTS)

122
00:14:27,280 --> 00:14:28,281
(SCREAMING)

123
00:14:34,600 --> 00:14:35,806
(INFANT CRYING)

124
00:14:54,720 --> 00:14:56,290
(COOING)

125
00:15:05,480 --> 00:15:07,164
(SNARLING)

126
00:15:09,880 --> 00:15:11,325
(ROARS)

127
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:19,731
JANE: The most dangerous beast
in Africa is so powerful,

128
00:15:19,880 --> 00:15:23,327
it can snap a crocodile's back
with a single bite.

129
00:15:24,520 --> 00:15:26,090
(WHISPERING)

130
00:15:26,160 --> 00:15:27,685
Anyone?

131
00:15:29,120 --> 00:15:31,202
MARY: Is it a hippopotamus?

132
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:34,921
Yes! Precisely. Well done, Mary.

133
00:15:37,600 --> 00:15:38,601
Now,

134
00:15:38,760 --> 00:15:42,526
can anyone tell me
what my favorite bird sounds like?

135
00:15:43,560 --> 00:15:45,289
- Anyone?
- (WHISPERING)

136
00:15:49,680 --> 00:15:51,125
(MIMICKING BIRD'S CALL)

137
00:16:02,080 --> 00:16:03,650
BOY: How do you travel through the jungle?

138
00:16:03,800 --> 00:16:05,450
Why'd you leave the jungle?

139
00:16:05,560 --> 00:16:07,483
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

140
00:16:07,560 --> 00:16:08,561
BOY 2: Look at his hands!

141
00:16:09,560 --> 00:16:11,562
CHILDREN: Whoa!

142
00:16:12,600 --> 00:16:14,728
I grew up running on all fours.

143
00:16:15,560 --> 00:16:17,881
It changed the bone structure.

144
00:16:22,240 --> 00:16:24,481
BOY 3: Do you swing on things inside?

145
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:26,768
Like, when you go upstairs?

146
00:16:26,960 --> 00:16:29,884
Oh, I never take the stairs.

147
00:16:30,080 --> 00:16:31,411
I usually take the curtains.

148
00:16:31,560 --> 00:16:32,641
BOY 3: Amazing!

149
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:36,330
Is it true your mum was a monkey?

150
00:16:38,040 --> 00:16:40,042
Well, of course not.

151
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:42,407
My mum was Alice Clayton.

152
00:16:46,080 --> 00:16:47,923
I can't wait to see Wasimbu again.

153
00:16:48,080 --> 00:16:49,525
- How many children would he have now?
- Jane.

154
00:16:49,680 --> 00:16:51,728
We know about Keko. She's what, four?

155
00:16:51,880 --> 00:16:53,644
- Everyone would have children.
- Jane.

156
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:55,689
I mean, eight years
just feels like a lifetime!

157
00:16:55,840 --> 00:16:57,126
This isn't a holiday.

158
00:16:57,280 --> 00:16:59,442
How many corsets does a diplomat bring?

159
00:16:59,600 --> 00:17:01,409
I can't take you.

160
00:17:02,600 --> 00:17:04,523
- I say zero.
- Four.

161
00:17:05,280 --> 00:17:08,648
I suppose a British lady should faint
at least twice to justify the silly title.

162
00:17:08,840 --> 00:17:09,841
It isn't safe there.

163
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:11,650
Of course it's not safe there, John!

164
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:15,447
You take a nap in the wrong place,
you've got a 50-50 chance of being eaten.

165
00:17:16,680 --> 00:17:18,762
Ladies. Albert.

166
00:17:25,920 --> 00:17:28,810
You can't possibly still think
there is a danger, John.

167
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:35,322
And you haven't spoken his name in years.

168
00:17:38,160 --> 00:17:39,491
Talk to me.

169
00:17:41,240 --> 00:17:43,481
Mbonga is not my concern.

170
00:17:44,120 --> 00:17:45,326
You are.

171
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:47,923
We lost a baby.

172
00:17:48,080 --> 00:17:51,163
The last thing you need is more stress.

173
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:55,251
Yes, well...

174
00:17:56,320 --> 00:17:58,049
Thank you for the reminder.

175
00:17:59,360 --> 00:18:02,204
Well, in case you forgot,
we both grew up there.

176
00:18:03,560 --> 00:18:05,961
So, perhaps I will fulfill your duties
for the Queen,

177
00:18:06,120 --> 00:18:10,000
and you can stay here hybridizing
coconuts and playing ping-pong.

178
00:18:12,600 --> 00:18:15,046
(SIGHS) I want to go home.

179
00:18:15,200 --> 00:18:16,361
This is our home.

180
00:18:19,280 --> 00:18:21,362
Trying to keep me here won't work!

181
00:18:21,560 --> 00:18:22,686
(OUTER DOOR SLAMS)

182
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:24,047
(DOOR OPENS)

183
00:18:44,840 --> 00:18:46,330
(CHITTERING)

184
00:19:17,840 --> 00:19:18,841
(GROWLING)

185
00:19:25,920 --> 00:19:26,921
(SCREAMING)

186
00:19:27,960 --> 00:19:29,405
- (ROARING)
- (SCREECHING)

187
00:19:38,600 --> 00:19:39,601
(SCREAMING)

188
00:19:45,760 --> 00:19:46,761
(ROARING)

189
00:19:53,720 --> 00:19:54,960
(GROWLING)

190
00:20:08,400 --> 00:20:09,401
(GROWLS)

191
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:50,404
JOHN CLAYTON II: John, my son,
you are the heir to Greystoke, our future.

192
00:21:53,080 --> 00:21:55,765
England is your home,
not this wretched place.

193
00:21:57,400 --> 00:21:58,401
If I don't survive,

194
00:22:00,920 --> 00:22:03,321
I pray that someone will save you.

195
00:22:38,800 --> 00:22:39,801
(GRUNTS)

196
00:23:00,600 --> 00:23:03,524
Promise me you'll stay
with the Kuba the whole time.

197
00:23:52,240 --> 00:23:54,129
(GEORGE LAUGHS)

198
00:23:54,200 --> 00:23:55,725
GEORGE: Not a chance, ma'am.

199
00:23:55,880 --> 00:24:00,169
A kick from one of these Walker Colts
is pretty nasty.

200
00:24:00,320 --> 00:24:02,402
As a matter of fact,
that's why they went out of style.

201
00:24:02,560 --> 00:24:05,689
Pretty little ladies like you
kept knocking themselves in the face.

202
00:24:05,760 --> 00:24:06,886
(JANE SCOFFS)

203
00:24:06,960 --> 00:24:09,850
I'll bet I could hit that log
over there, first try.

204
00:24:09,920 --> 00:24:11,046
Oh! (CHUCKLES)

205
00:24:15,480 --> 00:24:16,720
JOHN: Jane?

206
00:25:01,560 --> 00:25:04,166
He's known them since they were cubs.

207
00:25:17,080 --> 00:25:18,445
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

208
00:25:35,160 --> 00:25:36,969
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Force Publique, move aside.

209
00:25:37,120 --> 00:25:39,646
Force Publique, move aside!

210
00:25:41,200 --> 00:25:45,765
I want port of entry, I want port of
disembarkation for every passenger.

211
00:25:45,920 --> 00:25:47,490
Yes, sir. These are the last.

212
00:25:47,640 --> 00:25:49,961
- Sir.
- Thank you. Thank you.

213
00:26:05,320 --> 00:26:06,321
Excuse me, sir.

214
00:26:07,480 --> 00:26:08,641
The ledger.

215
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:10,290
Yes, thank you.

216
00:26:16,160 --> 00:26:17,321
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)

217
00:26:32,160 --> 00:26:33,366
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

218
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:40,010
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Gramophone, Mr. Rom's stateroom.

219
00:26:42,480 --> 00:26:43,561
ROM: Mr. Frum.

220
00:26:45,040 --> 00:26:46,644
Those crates go in the hold.

221
00:26:46,800 --> 00:26:50,771
Champagne? And music?
Your entire operation just fell apart.

222
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:52,007
Have faith, Mr. Frum.

223
00:26:52,160 --> 00:26:54,049
Faith is for missionaries.

224
00:26:54,200 --> 00:26:55,440
He gave you the slip.

225
00:26:57,320 --> 00:26:59,368
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Make sure the rest goes down below.

226
00:27:00,800 --> 00:27:03,883
ROM: Our invitation
has been snubbed, Mr. Frum.

227
00:27:04,040 --> 00:27:08,122
They jumped ship further up the coast,
and  they are on their own little tour home.

228
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:12,926
So, from Boma up to here
will take me three days.

229
00:27:13,080 --> 00:27:16,050
I shall deliver Tarzan and return.

230
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:17,850
A week's delay.

231
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:20,526
You're in no position
to ask for anything, Mr. Rom.

232
00:27:20,680 --> 00:27:23,445
Your king's payment was due
three months ago.

233
00:27:23,600 --> 00:27:24,681
Yes.

234
00:27:27,800 --> 00:27:28,801
(BELL RINGING)

235
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:35,722
I manipulated my firm
to keep this deal alive.

236
00:27:35,920 --> 00:27:38,401
You agreed because you'll get
stinking rich, so don't get trutty.

237
00:27:38,560 --> 00:27:39,846
Now, you must buy us more time.

238
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,128
I already bought all the time...

239
00:27:42,280 --> 00:27:43,441
Look, it's really very easy.

240
00:27:43,640 --> 00:27:46,970
You sail out to the arriving fleet and
tell them payment must be made in Boma

241
00:27:47,120 --> 00:27:48,804
for security reasons.

242
00:28:06,880 --> 00:28:08,450
Opar had better not be a myth.

243
00:28:11,760 --> 00:28:14,889
Bring me the rest,
and you'll have your mercenaries.

244
00:28:15,040 --> 00:28:16,724
But if you fail to make good this time,

245
00:28:16,920 --> 00:28:19,571
my firm will go to the Belgian parliament
for compensation.

246
00:28:19,760 --> 00:28:23,402
Your king will lose this land,
and who do you think he will blame?

247
00:28:23,560 --> 00:28:25,085
Leon Rom?

248
00:28:58,000 --> 00:28:59,365
Tarzan, you look funny.

249
00:28:59,640 --> 00:29:01,130
(CHUCKLES)

250
00:29:01,280 --> 00:29:03,647
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

251
00:29:04,080 --> 00:29:05,366
(LAUGHING)

252
00:29:18,760 --> 00:29:20,046
Wukonseeni!

253
00:29:20,200 --> 00:29:22,282
- Sangonini!
- Janey!

254
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:24,843
- Sangonini.
- Ton moh nah nah ha lah.

255
00:29:25,360 --> 00:29:26,771
(ALL CHEERING)

256
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:28,604
(ALL SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

257
00:29:33,520 --> 00:29:34,521
JANE: Keikoo.

258
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:37,925
(BOTH SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

259
00:29:46,560 --> 00:29:47,561
(LAUGHS)

260
00:29:51,320 --> 00:29:52,321
- (SINGING STOPS)
- (ALL CHEERING)

261
00:29:57,880 --> 00:29:58,881
Wasimbu?

262
00:29:59,640 --> 00:30:01,404
Oh, my God!

263
00:30:05,160 --> 00:30:07,845
Janey Porter. Welcome home.

264
00:30:08,720 --> 00:30:10,324
(ALL CONTINUE SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

265
00:30:17,480 --> 00:30:21,567
WASIMBU: As is custom,
no one has entered until you returned.

266
00:30:30,520 --> 00:30:32,648
This is where Jane grew up.

267
00:30:34,400 --> 00:30:37,210
Her father taught English in the village.

268
00:30:48,480 --> 00:30:50,448
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

269
00:31:06,400 --> 00:31:09,210
(BOTH SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

270
00:31:21,440 --> 00:31:23,283
Well, I'm not going to drink
some foaming cup of

271
00:31:23,480 --> 00:31:25,528
you-know-what-it-is-and-won't-tell-me.

272
00:31:26,480 --> 00:31:27,481
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

273
00:31:29,800 --> 00:31:31,086
(ALL LAUGHING)

274
00:31:31,480 --> 00:31:33,608
GEORGE:
That's funny to everybody, huh? Mmm-hmm.

275
00:31:34,960 --> 00:31:36,769
- (COUGHING)
- (ALL LAUGHING)

276
00:31:37,640 --> 00:31:38,641
Whoo!

277
00:31:46,920 --> 00:31:48,809
(PEOPLE SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

278
00:31:55,520 --> 00:31:57,568
They're singing the legend of Tarzan.

279
00:31:59,560 --> 00:32:02,370
For many moons,
he was thought to be an evil spirit.

280
00:32:03,520 --> 00:32:05,204
A ghost in the trees.

281
00:32:10,960 --> 00:32:12,200
(ROARING)

282
00:32:15,680 --> 00:32:18,365
They speak of his power
over the animals of the jungle.

283
00:32:20,440 --> 00:32:22,647
Because his spirit came from them.

284
00:32:32,920 --> 00:32:34,081
He understood them

285
00:32:37,040 --> 00:32:38,371
and learned to conquer them.

286
00:32:44,640 --> 00:32:48,406
His ape mother, Kala,
loved him as her own,

287
00:32:48,560 --> 00:32:52,246
and his ape brother, Akut,
treated him with kindness and respect.

288
00:32:56,880 --> 00:32:57,881
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

289
00:32:59,560 --> 00:33:02,131
He considered all men to be his enemies,

290
00:33:02,720 --> 00:33:05,929
since other tribes would hunt his troop
as a rite of passage.

291
00:33:08,080 --> 00:33:09,206
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

292
00:33:17,720 --> 00:33:20,371
JANE: Chief Muviro knew what he was.

293
00:33:20,560 --> 00:33:24,961
He was good to him,
since no man ever started with less.

294
00:33:25,320 --> 00:33:26,924
(SINGING CONTINUES)

295
00:33:36,600 --> 00:33:38,443
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

296
00:33:51,960 --> 00:33:52,961
John?

297
00:33:59,080 --> 00:34:00,764
(JOHN MIMICKING BIRD CALLING)

298
00:34:04,840 --> 00:34:07,366
Blue-bottom rufous towhee.

299
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:10,723
Mating call.

300
00:34:12,960 --> 00:34:15,042
Be still, my beating heart.

301
00:34:24,920 --> 00:34:26,285
(JOHN MIMICKING BIRD CALLING)

302
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,650
Mandrill.

303
00:34:29,880 --> 00:34:32,121
Also a mating call.

304
00:34:36,960 --> 00:34:38,246
(JOHN GROWLING)

305
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:42,485
Cheetah.

306
00:34:43,640 --> 00:34:45,005
Mating call.

307
00:34:45,840 --> 00:34:48,969
JANE: Ten, nine,

308
00:34:49,120 --> 00:34:52,010
eight, seven,

309
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:57,403
six, five, four,

310
00:34:58,680 --> 00:34:59,841
three,

311
00:35:03,600 --> 00:35:04,647
two...

312
00:35:14,880 --> 00:35:17,531
I know you took my handkerchief.

313
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:21,367
We're from America,
and my father is a professor.

314
00:35:21,520 --> 00:35:24,364
So, I didn't grow up believing in spirits.

315
00:35:33,040 --> 00:35:34,041
Hello.

316
00:35:36,200 --> 00:35:37,725
You're welcome to have it.

317
00:35:40,560 --> 00:35:42,324
Will you speak to me?

318
00:35:57,320 --> 00:35:58,321
Um...

319
00:36:03,960 --> 00:36:04,961
(CHUCKLES)

320
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:14,526
You must know that this is very peculiar.

321
00:36:14,600 --> 00:36:16,011
(SNIFFS)

322
00:36:16,080 --> 00:36:20,290
I'm not sure my father would
find this very appropriate.

323
00:36:20,360 --> 00:36:22,010
(CONTINUES SNIFFING)

324
00:36:22,080 --> 00:36:23,844
But, um... (CLEARS THROAT)

325
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:27,288
We must make an effort
to embrace customs...

326
00:36:29,720 --> 00:36:32,166
Oh! I don't think so, wild man!

327
00:36:32,400 --> 00:36:33,686
(EXHALES)

328
00:36:34,400 --> 00:36:35,561
No, no, no. Wait!

329
00:37:19,200 --> 00:37:20,850
(FAINT CRY IN THE DISTANCE)

330
00:37:34,120 --> 00:37:36,168
(PANICKED CHATTER IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

331
00:37:43,520 --> 00:37:45,010
(WOMEN SOBBING)

332
00:37:56,720 --> 00:37:58,210
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

333
00:38:01,880 --> 00:38:04,121
I speak many languages.

334
00:38:05,960 --> 00:38:07,200
(GUN COCKS)

335
00:38:07,280 --> 00:38:08,327
Kneel!

336
00:38:10,160 --> 00:38:13,050
Kuba chief never kneels.

337
00:38:13,240 --> 00:38:14,765
(OFFICERS SHOUTING)

338
00:38:16,240 --> 00:38:18,686
- OFFICER: Down! All of you!
- Get down!

339
00:38:19,320 --> 00:38:20,401
Take aim!

340
00:38:22,200 --> 00:38:23,201
(GROANS)

341
00:38:26,400 --> 00:38:27,970
(OFFICERS CONTINUE SHOUTING)

342
00:38:30,240 --> 00:38:31,730
Come on!

343
00:38:32,320 --> 00:38:33,321
(GUN COCKS)

344
00:38:33,440 --> 00:38:34,441
(GRUNTING)

345
00:38:40,240 --> 00:38:41,241
(CHOKING)

346
00:38:44,640 --> 00:38:45,641
(ALL GRUNTING)

347
00:38:53,400 --> 00:38:54,890
OFFICER: Hold him still!

348
00:39:00,440 --> 00:39:02,363
Tighter! Tighter!

349
00:39:02,440 --> 00:39:03,441
(GRUNTING)

350
00:39:05,160 --> 00:39:08,164
You ain't so tough,
you grotty little monkey boy.

351
00:39:15,760 --> 00:39:17,125
- (GRUNTING)
- (ROPES TIGHTENING)

352
00:39:23,120 --> 00:39:24,849
Some legend, Mr. Rom.

353
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:27,526
Chief Mbonga will be disappointed.

354
00:39:32,040 --> 00:39:33,644
Round up 10 of the strongest.

355
00:39:34,320 --> 00:39:36,641
- We'll need porters.
- Yes, sir.

356
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:38,206
This guy right here, sir.

357
00:39:38,280 --> 00:39:39,566
(KUBA PEOPLE PROTESTING)

358
00:39:39,640 --> 00:39:41,642
Grab him, men. You're coming with me!

359
00:39:53,400 --> 00:39:54,447
JANE: Let go of me!

360
00:39:54,960 --> 00:39:56,405
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

361
00:39:58,880 --> 00:40:00,006
John!

362
00:40:00,600 --> 00:40:02,329
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- (JANE GRUNTING)

363
00:40:06,320 --> 00:40:07,606
Get off! John!

364
00:40:07,800 --> 00:40:10,724
Must have been something
the first moment you saw her.

365
00:40:12,200 --> 00:40:14,771
After all the negresses and baboons.

366
00:40:15,120 --> 00:40:16,121
(MIMICKING BABOONS)

367
00:40:16,440 --> 00:40:17,851
(MAJOR KERCKHOVER LAUGHING)

368
00:40:19,680 --> 00:40:20,966
JANE: John!

369
00:40:23,280 --> 00:40:24,645
- (GUN FIRES)
- (GROANS)

370
00:40:30,640 --> 00:40:31,641
(GROANS)

371
00:40:38,160 --> 00:40:39,161
(GUNS COCKING)

372
00:40:44,440 --> 00:40:45,680
(PANICKED CHATTER)

373
00:41:04,800 --> 00:41:05,801
(GRUNTING)

374
00:41:11,040 --> 00:41:13,042
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Mr. Rom, we'll bring him down.

375
00:41:13,240 --> 00:41:14,844
Go! Go!

376
00:41:15,480 --> 00:41:16,481
(GRUNTS)

377
00:41:21,280 --> 00:41:22,327
Get the Maxims loaded!

378
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:23,881
Hurry!

379
00:41:26,760 --> 00:41:27,761
(GROANS)

380
00:41:31,400 --> 00:41:34,609
Focus fire on the boilers.
Below the chimney.

381
00:41:38,400 --> 00:41:39,811
Pull away!

382
00:41:43,360 --> 00:41:44,566
Where do you think you're going?

383
00:41:49,280 --> 00:41:50,691
(JANE BREATHING HEAVILY)

384
00:41:55,720 --> 00:41:57,643
I need you to scream for me.

385
00:42:00,120 --> 00:42:01,690
Like a damsel?

386
00:42:02,360 --> 00:42:03,361
(SPITS)

387
00:42:13,520 --> 00:42:15,170
No matter.

388
00:42:16,120 --> 00:42:18,122
He's Tarzan, you're Jane.

389
00:42:20,760 --> 00:42:22,250
He'll come for you.

390
00:42:25,320 --> 00:42:26,321
(GRUNTS)

391
00:42:37,800 --> 00:42:40,167
John! John!

392
00:42:44,120 --> 00:42:46,088
John! John...

393
00:42:47,760 --> 00:42:48,761
(GASPING)

394
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:05,843
(WOMEN SOBBING)

395
00:43:11,320 --> 00:43:12,810
They came for me, Kwete.

396
00:43:12,960 --> 00:43:14,405
KWETE: This was not done by you.

397
00:43:16,480 --> 00:43:17,845
Do you know who they were?

398
00:43:18,600 --> 00:43:21,285
We've heard of whites
that come and fight for money,

399
00:43:21,440 --> 00:43:23,010
do not wear Belgian colors...

400
00:43:23,200 --> 00:43:24,531
Called Force Publique.

401
00:43:25,640 --> 00:43:28,166
The man I interviewed in Belgium
told me about them.

402
00:43:28,320 --> 00:43:29,845
Did anyone mention a man named Rom?

403
00:43:31,120 --> 00:43:32,645
Nobody gave up any names.

404
00:43:32,800 --> 00:43:36,930
But Leon Rom
is King Leopold's envoy to the Congo.

405
00:43:38,480 --> 00:43:39,606
Any other revelations?

406
00:43:40,680 --> 00:43:42,205
Not from me.

407
00:43:43,160 --> 00:43:44,491
Why do you say they came to get you?

408
00:43:49,880 --> 00:43:50,881
(GRUNTS)

409
00:43:52,200 --> 00:43:56,205
JOHN: The boat is traveling upstream,
which will slow it down.

410
00:43:56,400 --> 00:43:58,482
We should get to Mbonga's mountain
before them

411
00:43:58,640 --> 00:44:01,564
if we take this route
through the Mangani lands.

412
00:44:01,720 --> 00:44:02,801
How do you know where they're going?

413
00:44:02,960 --> 00:44:05,122
- KWETE: This route...
- JOHN: It's longer.

414
00:44:05,280 --> 00:44:07,044
But it is where they are building
the railroad.

415
00:44:07,200 --> 00:44:08,850
We can ride it part of the way.

416
00:44:10,240 --> 00:44:11,241
Good.

417
00:44:13,280 --> 00:44:14,520
GEORGE: John?

418
00:44:15,400 --> 00:44:16,731
John?

419
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:19,490
John!

420
00:44:20,360 --> 00:44:22,567
Fine! I'm still coming with you.

421
00:44:23,400 --> 00:44:24,845
You can't keep up.

422
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:28,730
I might not be able to keep up with Tarzan,
but I sure as hell can keep up with you.

423
00:44:28,880 --> 00:44:30,086
It is not wise.

424
00:44:30,240 --> 00:44:31,844
Falling behind means certain death.

425
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:33,889
I spent over half my life in the wilds.

426
00:44:34,040 --> 00:44:36,247
Besides, nobody here
is better than me with a rifle.

427
00:44:36,440 --> 00:44:39,728
That one right there, he'd still be
choked out redder than a cardinal's ass

428
00:44:39,880 --> 00:44:41,450
if it weren't for me. And that's...

429
00:44:41,760 --> 00:44:42,807
(YELPS)

430
00:44:42,880 --> 00:44:44,325
You think I care about my life?

431
00:44:44,480 --> 00:44:45,766
Get your mitts off me!

432
00:44:46,360 --> 00:44:48,681
- If you had just...
- If I'd just what?

433
00:44:48,840 --> 00:44:50,490
Left you in England in your castle?

434
00:44:51,800 --> 00:44:55,805
They have my wife and their families.

435
00:45:47,840 --> 00:45:52,323
Whoever you are,
we're here by royal invitation.

436
00:45:52,520 --> 00:45:54,682
As guests of King Leopold.

437
00:45:55,760 --> 00:45:59,162
Lady Clayton,
I orchestrated the invitation.

438
00:46:00,480 --> 00:46:02,209
And you were not included.

439
00:46:03,160 --> 00:46:05,162
Nor was Dr. Williams.

440
00:46:07,880 --> 00:46:12,363
A tribe of savages
is trying to tear your husband apart

441
00:46:12,520 --> 00:46:14,409
and maybe butcher him and eat him.

442
00:46:15,080 --> 00:46:17,128
And I'm going to deliver him to them.

443
00:46:17,280 --> 00:46:18,691
And once they've dispatched with him,

444
00:46:18,880 --> 00:46:21,201
(LAUGHING)
Dr. Williams will not be left as a witness,

445
00:46:21,360 --> 00:46:22,600
that's clear.

446
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:26,843
Which begs the question,

447
00:46:27,920 --> 00:46:29,809
where does that leave you?

448
00:46:36,800 --> 00:46:39,804
You'll notice
none of the natives are smiling.

449
00:46:47,120 --> 00:46:49,043
That one's your friend?

450
00:46:51,240 --> 00:46:52,241
They all are.

451
00:47:00,640 --> 00:47:02,927
You do know
that the right side of your mustache

452
00:47:03,080 --> 00:47:05,447
is just a little lower than the left?

453
00:47:30,640 --> 00:47:31,641
(PANTING)

454
00:47:43,120 --> 00:47:44,690
(GEORGE WHEEZING)

455
00:47:46,720 --> 00:47:47,767
(GROWLS)

456
00:47:48,480 --> 00:47:49,845
GEORGE: John!

457
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:51,570
John!

458
00:48:05,160 --> 00:48:06,889
(GEORGE PANTING)

459
00:48:09,040 --> 00:48:10,041
(COUGHING)

460
00:48:15,120 --> 00:48:16,121
Different kind of wilds.

461
00:48:23,480 --> 00:48:24,720
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS IN THE DISTANCE)

462
00:48:26,160 --> 00:48:28,640
How are we supposed to catch
a train going 40 miles an hour?

463
00:48:33,160 --> 00:48:34,685
Gravity.

464
00:48:50,440 --> 00:48:51,521
Shit!

465
00:48:53,320 --> 00:48:54,321
(GEORGE SCREAMING)

466
00:48:54,560 --> 00:48:56,289
(GEORGE GROANING)

467
00:49:01,840 --> 00:49:02,841
(PANTING)

468
00:49:23,760 --> 00:49:24,966
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

469
00:49:31,680 --> 00:49:32,681
(PANTING)

470
00:49:58,680 --> 00:50:00,125
Climb on my back.

471
00:50:04,120 --> 00:50:05,121
(GEORGE GRUNTS)

472
00:50:05,280 --> 00:50:06,611
Right. Legs, too.

473
00:50:08,080 --> 00:50:09,081
(GRUNTING)

474
00:50:12,360 --> 00:50:15,125
Don't think for a second
you're saving my life.

475
00:50:17,240 --> 00:50:18,685
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

476
00:50:21,960 --> 00:50:23,041
(GEORGE SCREAMING)

477
00:50:40,120 --> 00:50:41,121
(THUDDING)

478
00:51:26,840 --> 00:51:28,171
(ALL GRUNTING)

479
00:51:40,800 --> 00:51:41,801
(GRUNTS)

480
00:51:46,840 --> 00:51:49,081
Give me the keys to the chains.

481
00:51:49,280 --> 00:51:50,281
(GLASS SHATTERING)

482
00:51:57,880 --> 00:51:58,881
(BOTH GRUNTING)

483
00:52:04,240 --> 00:52:05,241
JOHN: Are you the commander?

484
00:52:05,400 --> 00:52:06,447
Don't tell him anything.

485
00:52:07,680 --> 00:52:08,681
(GUN COCKING)

486
00:52:08,760 --> 00:52:11,684
Those are some mighty big earlobes
you got there, son.

487
00:52:14,200 --> 00:52:15,201
(GUN FIRES)

488
00:52:17,880 --> 00:52:20,247
Do you think that was a lucky shot?

489
00:52:21,200 --> 00:52:24,807
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

490
00:52:27,080 --> 00:52:28,525
I'm just an engineer for the bridge.

491
00:52:29,800 --> 00:52:32,644
And how many men
have been enslaved to build your bridge?

492
00:52:33,920 --> 00:52:35,445
Eight hundred.

493
00:52:35,600 --> 00:52:38,001
Plus, this group of natives.

494
00:52:38,160 --> 00:52:41,323
Please, I'm here to build bridges
for Monsieur Rom's new army.

495
00:52:41,480 --> 00:52:42,686
I have no part in that.

496
00:52:43,840 --> 00:52:44,921
What army?

497
00:52:50,920 --> 00:52:54,122
ENGINEER: The railroads,
combined with the navigable rivers

498
00:52:55,240 --> 00:52:59,768
put 60% of Congo
within three days of a fort.

499
00:53:01,920 --> 00:53:04,605
The forts are done,
but the army has not come.

500
00:53:04,760 --> 00:53:06,000
Where are they?

501
00:53:06,200 --> 00:53:07,281
I don't know.

502
00:53:07,920 --> 00:53:09,570
They were supposed to be here months ago.

503
00:53:10,240 --> 00:53:12,561
But they said
the King is yet to pay for them.

504
00:53:12,720 --> 00:53:14,165
How many are there?

505
00:53:16,560 --> 00:53:17,766
Twenty thousand.

506
00:53:19,280 --> 00:53:21,328
And they are not regular soldiers.

507
00:53:22,440 --> 00:53:24,283
They are mercenaries.

508
00:53:24,800 --> 00:53:26,882
Known to enjoy killing for a living.

509
00:53:27,040 --> 00:53:29,008
Twenty thousand men, 50 forts.

510
00:53:29,160 --> 00:53:33,643
That's 400 bloodthirsty bastards
armed with a Maxim gun

511
00:53:33,800 --> 00:53:35,802
and repeating rifles at each one.

512
00:53:35,960 --> 00:53:39,806
He'll end up enslaving the entire country
to get what he wants.

513
00:53:40,480 --> 00:53:42,164
People won't stand a chance.

514
00:53:43,680 --> 00:53:45,523
What is Mr. Rom's part in this?

515
00:53:45,680 --> 00:53:48,923
It's his plan.
He is in charge of all of it.

516
00:53:51,600 --> 00:53:54,809
They expect
he will be named Governor General soon.

517
00:54:02,760 --> 00:54:04,171
JANE: No, no, no. Wait!

518
00:54:10,320 --> 00:54:11,890
Wait! Please!

519
00:54:21,840 --> 00:54:22,841
(ROARING)

520
00:54:23,160 --> 00:54:24,161
(GASPS)

521
00:54:27,840 --> 00:54:28,841
(ROARING)

522
00:54:38,160 --> 00:54:40,242
(GROANING)

523
00:54:56,720 --> 00:54:57,721
(WAILING)

524
00:55:23,720 --> 00:55:25,210
(WAILING)

525
00:55:31,840 --> 00:55:32,921
(CONTINUES WAILING)

526
00:55:55,240 --> 00:55:56,241
(GUNS COCKING)

527
00:56:00,360 --> 00:56:01,521
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

528
00:56:01,720 --> 00:56:03,324
Shut it, clucker!

529
00:56:10,080 --> 00:56:11,081
(MEN LAUGHING)

530
00:56:11,160 --> 00:56:15,768
Now, if you do
anything unladylike in there,

531
00:56:17,200 --> 00:56:18,804
he drowns.

532
00:56:38,160 --> 00:56:39,764
JANE: Enjoying your peep show?

533
00:56:43,160 --> 00:56:46,528
Of course I know
you can see me, Lady Clayton.

534
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:02,207
Are you a religious man, Mr. Rom?

535
00:57:02,360 --> 00:57:04,840
Oh. No. Madagascar spider silk.

536
00:57:08,160 --> 00:57:12,490
My priest purchased it for me
in Jerusalem when I was nine.

537
00:57:13,360 --> 00:57:16,204
Sounds like you and your priest
were awfully close.

538
00:57:16,880 --> 00:57:17,927
Why?

539
00:57:25,680 --> 00:57:30,488
I want you to know, I think your husband
had no right to bring you along.

540
00:57:30,640 --> 00:57:31,880
I brought myself, Mr. Rom.

541
00:57:32,040 --> 00:57:33,246
Of course.

542
00:57:33,400 --> 00:57:35,880
But he was supposed to be
the only casualty.

543
00:57:36,040 --> 00:57:39,840
Aside from the entire country of people
you're enslaving, of course.

544
00:57:41,320 --> 00:57:42,321
Would you pass the pepper?

545
00:57:49,200 --> 00:57:50,201
(GROANING)

546
00:58:15,960 --> 00:58:18,201
It can also serve as a necklace.

547
00:58:18,280 --> 00:58:19,406
(JANE SCOFFS)

548
00:58:30,720 --> 00:58:35,760
On my last visit to Europe,
I attended a few lectures at the Sorbonne.

549
00:58:36,440 --> 00:58:39,410
The King of France got a soft clap.

550
00:58:39,560 --> 00:58:41,722
Henry Morton Stanley,
a bastard orphan by birth,

551
00:58:41,880 --> 00:58:43,484
got a standing ovation.

552
00:58:44,640 --> 00:58:45,641
(CHUCKLES)

553
00:58:47,120 --> 00:58:49,009
People love a good story.

554
00:58:50,720 --> 00:58:54,327
Yeah, a few are born blue bloods,
like your husband.

555
00:58:57,960 --> 00:59:00,440
But everyone can relate
to a low-born scrapper

556
00:59:00,640 --> 00:59:04,281
who rescued his king from bankruptcy
and saved the honor of his nation.

557
00:59:04,440 --> 00:59:06,841
That is a man who will never be forgotten.

558
00:59:11,560 --> 00:59:14,131
My king's army is due in six days.

559
00:59:14,560 --> 00:59:17,803
All I've left to do
is deliver Tarzan to Chief Mbonga.

560
00:59:20,520 --> 00:59:23,922
(CHUCKLES)
Yeah, I'd hoped you'd recognize the name.

561
00:59:26,320 --> 00:59:29,483
I'm aware of his obsessive desire
to kill your husband,

562
00:59:29,640 --> 00:59:31,563
but I've yet to discover the cause.

563
00:59:31,720 --> 00:59:34,007
What did Tarzan do?

564
00:59:35,960 --> 00:59:38,008
He killed his only son.

565
00:59:41,200 --> 00:59:42,770
- Oh.
- Hmm.

566
00:59:45,880 --> 00:59:51,171
And get ready, because that is nothing
compared to what he will do to you.

567
00:59:52,520 --> 00:59:54,010
(INHALES DEEPLY)

568
00:59:55,200 --> 01:00:00,206
Your husband's wildness disturbs me
more than I can easily express.

569
01:00:01,680 --> 01:00:04,251
Whereas your spirit...

570
01:00:17,080 --> 01:00:19,560
My knife, please.

571
01:00:21,040 --> 01:00:22,565
Slowly.

572
01:00:22,760 --> 01:00:24,762
Your friend won't float.

573
01:00:35,040 --> 01:00:36,565
Thank you.

574
01:00:40,560 --> 01:00:41,561
(RINGS BELL)

575
01:00:42,560 --> 01:00:43,561
(DOOR OPENS)

576
01:00:46,960 --> 01:00:49,088
Lady Clayton's finished.

577
01:00:49,280 --> 01:00:50,281
(SCOFFS)

578
01:00:51,240 --> 01:00:55,211
A normal man can do the impossible
to save the woman he loves.

579
01:00:56,240 --> 01:00:59,050
My husband is no normal man.

580
01:01:03,560 --> 01:01:04,561
(DOOR CLOSES)

581
01:01:15,800 --> 01:01:17,245
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

582
01:01:28,760 --> 01:01:30,489
KWETE: You cannot go alone.

583
01:01:30,640 --> 01:01:32,847
They'd consider seven a raid.

584
01:01:33,600 --> 01:01:35,284
None of us would survive.

585
01:01:37,760 --> 01:01:40,889
This says it's against the law
to pay natives to work.

586
01:01:41,040 --> 01:01:44,522
And this is the ledger
of all the slaves taken so far.

587
01:01:44,720 --> 01:01:47,041
Slave labor, diamonds everywhere.

588
01:01:47,200 --> 01:01:51,091
Rom's going to make his monarch
the richest king in the world.

589
01:01:51,240 --> 01:01:52,685
Dr. Williams, you have your evidence.

590
01:01:54,480 --> 01:01:56,562
I'll take care of Rom.

591
01:01:57,760 --> 01:02:00,240
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

592
01:02:01,560 --> 01:02:03,801
Well, I have no choice.

593
01:02:03,960 --> 01:02:05,564
We'd lose two days going around.

594
01:02:05,720 --> 01:02:08,166
- Going around what?
- Mangani.

595
01:02:08,320 --> 01:02:10,800
Those gorillas you used to live with?

596
01:02:10,960 --> 01:02:12,166
They're not gorillas.

597
01:02:12,320 --> 01:02:14,891
Gorillas are gentle. Mangani are not.

598
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:25,844
I never left a friend in trouble,
or a partner in the lurch.

599
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:28,207
I'm not about to start now.

600
01:02:28,360 --> 01:02:30,806
Stop calling me "doctor."
My name's George.

601
01:02:31,400 --> 01:02:34,529
We'll keep your proof safe, George.

602
01:02:34,680 --> 01:02:35,681
I know.

603
01:02:36,800 --> 01:02:38,404
Meet us in Boma.

604
01:02:39,080 --> 01:02:40,081
If we don't make it back...

605
01:02:40,240 --> 01:02:42,641
We will. With your families.

606
01:02:42,800 --> 01:02:44,404
...get the books
to my grandfather in London.

607
01:02:46,000 --> 01:02:47,047
Still not waiting for you.

608
01:02:47,240 --> 01:02:48,480
Tell me something I didn't know.

609
01:02:48,680 --> 01:02:49,841
(ALL CHEERING)

610
01:03:01,280 --> 01:03:03,681
What I wouldn't give
for a horse right now.

611
01:03:05,200 --> 01:03:07,168
Why is it people don't ride zebras?

612
01:03:07,800 --> 01:03:09,882
Well, horses kick to escape.

613
01:03:10,040 --> 01:03:12,008
Zebras continue until you're dead.

614
01:03:12,920 --> 01:03:14,445
"Zee-bra," "zeb-ra."
"Tom-ay-to," "to-mah-to."

615
01:03:14,640 --> 01:03:17,371
It's nearly impossible to take the wild
out of something born to it.

616
01:03:17,560 --> 01:03:19,130
It seemed to have worked with you.

617
01:03:20,720 --> 01:03:23,644
Look, I feel foolish for asking,

618
01:03:24,320 --> 01:03:26,766
but can you really talk to the animals?

619
01:03:26,920 --> 01:03:30,402
You're an educated man, Dr. Williams.
You tell me.

620
01:03:32,320 --> 01:03:33,526
(OSTRICHES TRILLING)

621
01:03:39,400 --> 01:03:40,561
(SQUAWKING)

622
01:03:41,720 --> 01:03:43,449
(LAUGHING NERVOUSLY)
Hey! Hey, pretty lady!

623
01:03:46,320 --> 01:03:48,322
That's a male.

624
01:03:48,480 --> 01:03:50,244
He's warning us to stay clear.

625
01:03:51,400 --> 01:03:55,086
You're trying to tell me
those things are deadly?

626
01:03:55,240 --> 01:03:57,004
If you get too close,
he'll knock you to the ground

627
01:03:57,160 --> 01:03:59,481
and disembowel you
with those three-inch talons.

628
01:04:01,040 --> 01:04:02,644
No ostrich is going to kill me.

629
01:04:03,720 --> 01:04:05,370
Well, then try and ride him.

630
01:04:05,640 --> 01:04:08,166
(SCOFFS) You'd like that, wouldn't you?

631
01:04:08,920 --> 01:04:09,921
(SQUAWKS)

632
01:04:13,520 --> 01:04:14,521
Oh...

633
01:04:14,920 --> 01:04:16,763
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

634
01:04:25,120 --> 01:04:28,841
GEORGE: Damn!
That is one odious aroma. Whew, God!

635
01:04:29,000 --> 01:04:30,809
JOHN: Keep your voice low.

636
01:04:31,680 --> 01:04:33,364
(MANGANI GRUNTING)

637
01:04:35,160 --> 01:04:36,605
Is that them?

638
01:04:40,600 --> 01:04:42,329
(GROWLS)

639
01:04:42,920 --> 01:04:44,410
You don't want to do that, George.

640
01:04:44,960 --> 01:04:47,804
Kill one, and the rest won't stop
until they have torn you to pieces.

641
01:04:50,240 --> 01:04:51,765
So how do you want to play this, then?

642
01:04:52,360 --> 01:04:55,648
Their leader will come down,
and we'll fight.

643
01:04:57,480 --> 01:04:59,209
You're going to fight one of those?

644
01:04:59,360 --> 01:05:02,489
I wish. I have to fight Akut.

645
01:05:04,200 --> 01:05:06,123
He was my brother once.

646
01:05:06,760 --> 01:05:08,285
And now he'll consider me a deserter.

647
01:05:08,920 --> 01:05:12,288
Whatever happens, do not interfere.

648
01:05:13,160 --> 01:05:14,491
Understand?

649
01:05:14,560 --> 01:05:15,561
Mmm-hmm.

650
01:05:21,280 --> 01:05:22,520
GEORGE: Christ Almighty.

651
01:05:25,600 --> 01:05:27,011
That's Akut?

652
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:30,207
You sure you don't want me to shoot him?

653
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:35,490
Promise me.

654
01:05:38,840 --> 01:05:40,604
(EXHALING SHARPLY)

655
01:05:43,680 --> 01:05:45,523
(GROWLING)

656
01:05:47,720 --> 01:05:48,721
(GRUNTS)

657
01:05:59,520 --> 01:06:00,567
(ROARING)

658
01:06:13,560 --> 01:06:14,686
(GROANING)

659
01:06:20,760 --> 01:06:21,886
(GROANING LOUDLY)

660
01:06:33,400 --> 01:06:34,845
(GRUNTING)

661
01:06:49,920 --> 01:06:51,809
(GROANING)

662
01:06:59,920 --> 01:07:01,888
Get on your knees and bow.

663
01:07:02,440 --> 01:07:04,283
Right now!

664
01:07:04,920 --> 01:07:06,968
Expose your most vulnerable parts!

665
01:07:16,360 --> 01:07:17,361
(ROARING)

666
01:07:22,120 --> 01:07:24,282
(PANTING)
You want me to lick his nuts, too?

667
01:07:24,440 --> 01:07:25,965
If you want to live.

668
01:07:27,600 --> 01:07:28,806
George...

669
01:07:28,960 --> 01:07:30,121
I wasn't going to!

670
01:07:31,120 --> 01:07:32,485
Well, it looked like you were.

671
01:07:32,800 --> 01:07:33,801
(GRUNTING)

672
01:07:40,840 --> 01:07:42,842
(GROANING)

673
01:07:48,040 --> 01:07:49,041
(PANTING)

674
01:07:52,160 --> 01:07:53,491
GEORGE: Is he coming back?

675
01:07:53,720 --> 01:07:57,122
No. It was quite decisive.

676
01:07:57,280 --> 01:07:59,760
If this bite gets infected,
you're going to have problems.

677
01:08:00,320 --> 01:08:01,321
Then there is this.

678
01:08:06,040 --> 01:08:08,407
Now, you know
I was not going to lick his...

679
01:08:08,600 --> 01:08:09,601
It looked like you were.

680
01:08:09,680 --> 01:08:10,920
- Well, I wasn't.
- (GROANS LOUDLY)

681
01:08:15,240 --> 01:08:18,847
You aren't going anywhere
until we get this stitched up.

682
01:08:24,720 --> 01:08:26,529
Are you eating them?

683
01:08:27,040 --> 01:08:29,407
- Tastes like bacon.
- Ew.

684
01:08:29,480 --> 01:08:31,687
You get us a nice, fat snake,
I'd grub on that.

685
01:08:31,840 --> 01:08:35,162
Snake's good meat.
I ain't eating no damn ant.

686
01:08:35,320 --> 01:08:37,084
Well, suit yourself.

687
01:08:38,240 --> 01:08:39,605
And when you're finished,

688
01:08:39,800 --> 01:08:43,088
chew the flowers into a poultice
and wipe it on the cut with a rubber.

689
01:08:44,360 --> 01:08:45,850
It'll hold.

690
01:08:48,840 --> 01:08:52,008
Are you aware that you always say you're not
going to do something right before you do it?

691
01:08:52,160 --> 01:08:54,128
Yeah? Well...

692
01:08:54,280 --> 01:08:56,169
That's only since I've been saddled
with your company.

693
01:08:59,760 --> 01:09:01,046
How is it?

694
01:09:01,240 --> 01:09:02,844
It's manageable.

695
01:09:03,480 --> 01:09:04,766
Pain...

696
01:09:06,960 --> 01:09:09,122
I got too much experience with it.

697
01:09:15,680 --> 01:09:16,761
(SIGHS)

698
01:09:16,880 --> 01:09:19,247
The Civil War was dark fighting.

699
01:09:20,880 --> 01:09:22,769
But I was proud to be part of it.

700
01:09:25,120 --> 01:09:26,929
Changed me, though.

701
01:09:27,960 --> 01:09:31,646
Afterward, I was
a walking, talking powder keg.

702
01:09:34,440 --> 01:09:37,603
Joined up to fight
Maximilian down in Mexico.

703
01:09:39,480 --> 01:09:43,041
Then worked as an Indian fighter.

704
01:09:44,400 --> 01:09:46,562
Did both those for the money.

705
01:09:48,920 --> 01:09:50,684
I was young.

706
01:09:51,520 --> 01:09:53,409
But that's no excuse.

707
01:09:55,520 --> 01:09:56,521
(SIGHS)

708
01:09:58,560 --> 01:10:00,164
Mexico was bad.

709
01:10:02,280 --> 01:10:04,487
But what we did to the Indians...

710
01:10:04,560 --> 01:10:05,561
(SCOFFS)

711
01:10:14,480 --> 01:10:16,482
I'm no better than those Belgians.

712
01:10:19,520 --> 01:10:21,204
(ELEPHANTS TRUMPETING)

713
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:47,490
My old friend.

714
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:07,800
The Teke say an elephant's eyes
speak the greatest language.

715
01:11:10,600 --> 01:11:13,410
What else can make you feel so much
without a word?

716
01:11:14,040 --> 01:11:15,326
(BABY ELEPHANT TRUMPETING)

717
01:12:14,400 --> 01:12:15,481
(HIPPOS SNORTING AND GRUNTING)

718
01:12:33,760 --> 01:12:36,889
Is Mr. Rom ready
for some more scintillating conversation?

719
01:12:38,120 --> 01:12:41,841
He was the only reason
you weren't serviced.

720
01:12:42,040 --> 01:12:43,644
JANE: Serviced?

721
01:12:43,800 --> 01:12:45,768
Is that what your mother would call it?

722
01:12:49,640 --> 01:12:52,405
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

723
01:12:52,560 --> 01:12:53,607
Shut your mouth!

724
01:13:00,360 --> 01:13:01,805
(INHALES DEEPLY)

725
01:13:03,960 --> 01:13:04,961
(GRUNTING)

726
01:13:07,480 --> 01:13:10,643
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Stop the boat! Stop the boat!

727
01:13:10,880 --> 01:13:12,291
Turn it around!

728
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:15,206
(BOAT WHISTLE BLOWING)

729
01:13:18,160 --> 01:13:19,366
(PULLING UP CAGE)

730
01:13:19,480 --> 01:13:20,641
(GRUNTING)

731
01:13:29,120 --> 01:13:30,121
(GASPING)

732
01:13:34,080 --> 01:13:37,004
Stop shooting! You'll hit the girl!

733
01:13:49,160 --> 01:13:50,571
That woman.

734
01:13:51,640 --> 01:13:53,005
(BOTH PANTING)

735
01:14:06,520 --> 01:14:08,090
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

736
01:14:21,720 --> 01:14:22,721
Wait!

737
01:14:23,760 --> 01:14:26,604
They'll follow my tracks. Go and get help.

738
01:14:26,880 --> 01:14:27,881
Go!

739
01:14:33,680 --> 01:14:34,681
(GASPS)

740
01:14:36,120 --> 01:14:37,360
(ROARING)

741
01:15:27,120 --> 01:15:28,281
(GROWLING)

742
01:15:49,760 --> 01:15:50,841
(GROWLING)

743
01:15:59,480 --> 01:16:01,448
JANE: Promise you won't hurt them?

744
01:16:17,640 --> 01:16:19,847
- (GUN FIRES)
- No! Stop!

745
01:16:32,840 --> 01:16:34,410
(DISTANT SCREAMING)

746
01:16:37,960 --> 01:16:39,769
JANE: Please, stop!

747
01:16:41,360 --> 01:16:42,202
John!

748
01:16:42,560 --> 01:16:43,561
(PANTING)

749
01:16:50,680 --> 01:16:53,365
JANE: Stop! Stop it! Stop!

750
01:16:55,640 --> 01:16:56,641
(GRUNTING)

751
01:17:00,080 --> 01:17:01,286
Stop it! Please!

752
01:17:04,840 --> 01:17:07,002
Please! Please!

753
01:17:07,160 --> 01:17:08,207
Come on!

754
01:17:08,360 --> 01:17:09,691
MAJOR KERCKHOVER: Move out!

755
01:17:12,320 --> 01:17:13,606
(GROWLING)

756
01:17:26,200 --> 01:17:27,201
(PANTING)

757
01:17:36,720 --> 01:17:37,721
(ROARING)

758
01:17:38,160 --> 01:17:39,161
(GUN COCKING)

759
01:17:39,440 --> 01:17:40,680
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

760
01:17:52,600 --> 01:17:53,601
(GROWLS)

761
01:17:55,720 --> 01:17:56,721
(PANTING)

762
01:18:03,160 --> 01:18:04,207
(WHIMPERING)

763
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:17,365
(RUSTLING)

764
01:18:25,000 --> 01:18:26,001
(TWIG SNAPS)

765
01:18:26,200 --> 01:18:27,201
(GASPS)

766
01:18:27,280 --> 01:18:28,281
(GROWLING)

767
01:18:28,800 --> 01:18:30,802
- (ROARS)
- (JOHN GRUNTING)

768
01:18:56,640 --> 01:18:58,290
(JOHN ULULATING)

769
01:19:01,440 --> 01:19:03,522
MAJOR KERCKHOVER: What was that?

770
01:19:04,160 --> 01:19:05,207
ROM: Tarzan.

771
01:19:05,920 --> 01:19:08,082
Although it sounded
different than I thought.

772
01:19:09,400 --> 01:19:10,401
Better.

773
01:19:12,960 --> 01:19:14,564
(GEORGE PANTING)

774
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:26,126
Schmidt-Rubin.

775
01:19:26,320 --> 01:19:27,321
(GUN COCKING)

776
01:19:32,240 --> 01:19:33,446
John!

777
01:19:35,520 --> 01:19:36,521
John!

778
01:19:37,360 --> 01:19:38,361
Stop!

779
01:20:02,080 --> 01:20:03,445
(KALA SHRIEKING)

780
01:20:06,880 --> 01:20:07,881
(WHIMPERS)

781
01:20:22,600 --> 01:20:24,125
(EXHALING SHARPLY)

782
01:20:37,840 --> 01:20:38,841
(GASPS)

783
01:20:48,120 --> 01:20:49,121
(GRUNTS)

784
01:21:01,600 --> 01:21:02,806
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

785
01:21:54,720 --> 01:21:55,721
(GRUNTING)

786
01:22:02,200 --> 01:22:03,486
JANE: John!

787
01:22:10,960 --> 01:22:13,930
Now, you feel my pain.

788
01:22:16,560 --> 01:22:17,561
(YELLING)

789
01:22:30,120 --> 01:22:31,121
(ALL GRUNTING)

790
01:22:39,720 --> 01:22:41,006
(YELLS)

791
01:22:47,120 --> 01:22:48,929
(PANTING)

792
01:22:50,920 --> 01:22:52,604
(MBONGA CONTINUES YELLING)

793
01:23:16,520 --> 01:23:17,521
(BOTH PANTING)

794
01:23:21,760 --> 01:23:22,761
JOHN: I'm not your enemy.

795
01:23:22,920 --> 01:23:24,888
Rom's buying an army with your jewels.

796
01:23:25,040 --> 01:23:27,611
- They cannot touch us!
- You know nothing!

797
01:23:27,760 --> 01:23:30,764
Your lands are full of diamonds.
He'll come back for them.

798
01:23:31,520 --> 01:23:32,521
(GROANING)

799
01:24:00,280 --> 01:24:01,281
(GRUNTS)

800
01:24:01,440 --> 01:24:03,204
Your chief is under my knife!

801
01:24:03,960 --> 01:24:05,405
You are under my knife!

802
01:24:07,520 --> 01:24:09,124
Finish it.

803
01:24:09,280 --> 01:24:10,691
Finish it!

804
01:24:10,840 --> 01:24:11,966
Stop!

805
01:24:13,280 --> 01:24:15,089
(BOTH PANTING)

806
01:24:19,080 --> 01:24:22,004
Your son killed the only person
who ever cared about me.

807
01:24:22,200 --> 01:24:23,247
It was an animal.

808
01:24:23,400 --> 01:24:26,165
She was my mother.

809
01:24:29,360 --> 01:24:30,885
MBONGA: How was he to know?

810
01:24:32,800 --> 01:24:35,406
My son was just a boy!

811
01:24:36,080 --> 01:24:37,844
Not like you!

812
01:24:40,880 --> 01:24:43,008
Where was your honor?

813
01:24:55,200 --> 01:24:56,884
I had none.

814
01:24:59,120 --> 01:25:00,485
I had none.

815
01:25:02,400 --> 01:25:03,401
(AKUT ROARING)

816
01:25:23,320 --> 01:25:24,845
(MANGANI ROARING)

817
01:25:40,120 --> 01:25:42,691
GEORGE: Can we please just stop this?

818
01:25:42,840 --> 01:25:46,561
We won't get all of you, or you us.

819
01:25:46,720 --> 01:25:47,801
But Rom will.

820
01:25:48,720 --> 01:25:50,722
GEORGE: He'll wipe you out.

821
01:25:50,880 --> 01:25:54,327
Every last one of you.
Like you never even existed.

822
01:25:57,040 --> 01:25:59,168
You think that's impossible?

823
01:25:59,800 --> 01:26:02,326
You're looking at a man
that's seen it happen.

824
01:26:21,120 --> 01:26:22,485
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

825
01:26:30,480 --> 01:26:32,369
(JOHN ULULATING)

826
01:26:43,400 --> 01:26:45,084
(SIGHING IN RELIEF)

827
01:27:17,120 --> 01:27:18,326
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

828
01:27:36,120 --> 01:27:37,360
Rom's got the diamonds.

829
01:27:37,560 --> 01:27:40,325
There's 1,000 men down there
and 20,000 more on the way.

830
01:27:41,200 --> 01:27:42,281
We're screwed.

831
01:27:42,480 --> 01:27:43,527
Where are you going?

832
01:27:43,680 --> 01:27:45,011
To get some friends.

833
01:27:46,680 --> 01:27:48,045
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

834
01:28:04,120 --> 01:28:05,724
SOLDIER: All men, stations!

835
01:28:12,800 --> 01:28:14,131
(SHIP WHISTLE BLOWING)

836
01:28:31,880 --> 01:28:32,881
(GUN FIRES)

837
01:28:34,120 --> 01:28:35,406
(ROARING)

838
01:29:02,880 --> 01:29:05,770
It doesn't matter. He's too late.

839
01:29:16,800 --> 01:29:18,370
Move! Move!

840
01:29:18,520 --> 01:29:19,726
Fall back!

841
01:29:28,440 --> 01:29:29,441
(ROARS)

842
01:29:33,280 --> 01:29:34,406
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

843
01:29:34,480 --> 01:29:35,641
(MEN SHOUTING)

844
01:29:38,160 --> 01:29:39,161
(RATTLING)

845
01:29:43,600 --> 01:29:45,125
(PANICKED SCREAMING)

846
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:47,604
Bring her!

847
01:29:47,760 --> 01:29:48,761
(GRUNTING)

848
01:29:59,360 --> 01:30:00,407
(ALL PANTING)

849
01:30:08,600 --> 01:30:10,568
(KUBA SCREAMING)

850
01:30:12,480 --> 01:30:13,527
(SCREAMING)

851
01:30:16,040 --> 01:30:17,087
Grab the diamonds.

852
01:30:18,840 --> 01:30:19,966
Run!

853
01:30:22,240 --> 01:30:25,210
John! No! No! John!

854
01:30:27,560 --> 01:30:28,561
John!

855
01:30:44,360 --> 01:30:45,521
(BRAYS)

856
01:30:53,680 --> 01:30:55,808
Get to the boat! Move!

857
01:30:58,720 --> 01:30:59,721
(SCREAMING)

858
01:31:05,560 --> 01:31:06,561
(YELPS)

859
01:31:07,880 --> 01:31:09,530
We're coming! Hang on!

860
01:31:56,680 --> 01:31:57,841
John?

861
01:32:09,320 --> 01:32:10,731
FRUM: That's the payment.

862
01:32:13,280 --> 01:32:15,442
Lower the skiff, and don't dally.

863
01:32:22,080 --> 01:32:24,765
SOLDIER: Did you see him there?
Is he down there?

864
01:32:31,480 --> 01:32:34,962
1886 model Maxim machine gun.

865
01:32:37,560 --> 01:32:40,291
This is way better than my Walker Colts.

866
01:32:58,200 --> 01:32:59,531
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

867
01:33:04,240 --> 01:33:05,241
(SCREAMS)

868
01:33:13,080 --> 01:33:14,320
(GRUNTING)

869
01:33:50,920 --> 01:33:51,921
(CHOKING)

870
01:34:01,760 --> 01:34:02,807
FRUM: Mr. Rom!

871
01:34:05,720 --> 01:34:07,404
Mr. Frum, you portly coward!

872
01:34:07,560 --> 01:34:09,642
Come and get your diamonds!

873
01:34:14,640 --> 01:34:15,721
(GRUNTING)

874
01:34:16,640 --> 01:34:18,847
Farewell, sweet lord.

875
01:34:21,120 --> 01:34:23,168
Take Tarzan with you.

876
01:34:24,960 --> 01:34:26,849
The future belongs to me.

877
01:34:38,000 --> 01:34:39,240
(GROANING)

878
01:34:40,600 --> 01:34:42,090
(LOW GROWLING)

879
01:34:43,560 --> 01:34:44,766
(LOW GROWLING)

880
01:34:49,800 --> 01:34:50,926
What was that?

881
01:34:53,680 --> 01:34:54,920
Mating call.

882
01:35:02,040 --> 01:35:03,041
(GRUNTING)

883
01:35:28,280 --> 01:35:29,281
(GRUNTS)

884
01:35:29,800 --> 01:35:31,325
(CROCODILES GROWLING)

885
01:35:38,440 --> 01:35:39,441
(GASPING)

886
01:35:42,720 --> 01:35:43,960
Tarzan!

887
01:35:44,600 --> 01:35:46,250
Tarzan!

888
01:35:48,160 --> 01:35:49,047
John!

889
01:35:50,120 --> 01:35:50,962
John!

890
01:35:51,400 --> 01:35:53,801
(ROM SCREAMING)

891
01:35:57,480 --> 01:35:58,481
(HISSING)

892
01:36:26,240 --> 01:36:27,890
(ALL CHEERING)

893
01:36:51,440 --> 01:36:53,408
(ALL CHANTING)

894
01:36:55,760 --> 01:36:57,524
(CHEERING CONTINUES)

895
01:37:01,920 --> 01:37:02,921
(FRUM PANTING)

896
01:37:05,360 --> 01:37:06,850
(ALL ULULATING)

897
01:37:10,080 --> 01:37:12,242
We're not going to wade
into that mess for free.

898
01:37:15,200 --> 01:37:16,531
Raise the anchor!

899
01:38:00,640 --> 01:38:02,563
Ain't this a hell of a thing?

900
01:38:13,320 --> 01:38:14,810
- Nice outfit there, Janey.
- (CHUCKLES)

901
01:38:18,200 --> 01:38:20,202
You looked like you're about
to give me a hug.

902
01:38:21,640 --> 01:38:23,244
No, I wasn't.

903
01:38:24,480 --> 01:38:26,244
Looked like you were.

904
01:38:27,000 --> 01:38:28,570
(LAUGHING)

905
01:38:33,240 --> 01:38:34,765
(TRIBES CHEERING)

906
01:38:52,320 --> 01:38:54,607
GEORGE: An open letter
to His Serene Majesty,

907
01:38:54,760 --> 01:38:59,243
Leopold II, King of the Belgians.

908
01:38:59,400 --> 01:39:00,970
Every charge I'm about to bring

909
01:39:01,160 --> 01:39:03,527
against your Majesty's
personal government of the Congo

910
01:39:03,680 --> 01:39:06,126
has been carefully investigated.

911
01:39:06,280 --> 01:39:11,161
We have witnesses, documents,
letters, and official records

912
01:39:11,320 --> 01:39:14,961
to bring to your attention
and to verify our claims

913
01:39:15,120 --> 01:39:20,524
of your systematic abuse
and enslavement of the Congolese people.

914
01:39:23,040 --> 01:39:27,887
George Washington Williams.
July 18th, 1890.

915
01:40:06,880 --> 01:40:08,644
(KUBA WOMEN SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

916
01:40:39,360 --> 01:40:42,091
JANE: They are singing
the legend of Tarzan.

917
01:40:49,520 --> 01:40:52,808
For many moons,
he was thought to be an evil spirit.

918
01:40:54,440 --> 01:40:56,204
A ghost in the trees.

919
01:41:02,640 --> 01:41:06,486
They speak of his power
over the animals of the jungle.

920
01:41:08,200 --> 01:41:10,646
Because his spirit came from them.

921
01:41:13,800 --> 01:41:15,450
He understood them,

922
01:41:23,840 --> 01:41:26,320
and learned to be as one with them.